description:
Crow sized bird flew over my head with a moving jumble of stark black & white markings, landed in tree overhead, then flew off. In photo head not visible, but white markings on tail, wing, & under body. I've never seen a Magpie, but this is the only bird that fits what I saw. Somewhat out of it's range. 

This is the only shot I got.  Click on photo, then on "original" to zoom in.

More detailed writing,  Jan 25, 2020:
I was standing in my yard, looking at birds in this tree, my little digital camera in hand, when suddenly, from directly behind me, a black & white, broken chess game, the size of a crow, zoomed a few feet over my head. It swooped upward, landing inelegantly in the Eucalyptus, nearly overshooting the branch, as a circus clown or drunk person might. The Mockingbird and House Finches in the tree quickly scattered in different directions. There was already a lot of bird noise, like laughter in the air, so I can't say if it made any particular sounds. It never stopped changing positions on the branch as I snapped this photo. Its remarkably long, black tail is partly obscured by vegetation in this pic, and appears shorter than it was. While I zoomed the lens for a better view, the bird took off, flying in the direction it had come from. It was  in the tree about 15 seconds. I had never seen one of these before, so while it may not be a Magpie, I continue to insist it was not a Mockingbird.

description:
10 Foot male White shark stranded off Pleasure Point in Santa Cruz, CA yesterday. The white shark appeared to be sick and stranded. Despite team effort to release it back into the water; it continuously showed up back at the shore break.
The shark did not recover. Arranging follow up recovery and formal lab necropsy, hopefully at local UCSC lab or CDFW or NOAA facility to determine causes. Speculations are that this shark, a sub adult male white shark has stranded due to a Carnobacteroum Infection documented to be killing related species of mako sharks, salmon sharks and thresher sharks (Lamnid/Lamniforms sharks)
